1 Introduction 
 
As an emerging paradigm, cloud computing can provide scalable computing resources such as infrastructure, platform, and software for users on a pay-as-you-use business model [1]. With its booming development, cloud computing attracts a large number of users to outsource their big data storage and computations to the cloud [2]. One could send his/her data to a cloud for processing (e.g., dimensionality reduction, prediction, recommendation, and clustering). There are, however, security and privacy concerns (e.g., exposure of user privacy and business information, insider attacks, and inference threats) when data are outsourced to the cloud [3], [4]. A naive mitigation strategy is to encrypt sensitive data (e.g., social relationships and personal preferences) prior to sending such data to the cloud. A major research challenge is to securely and effectively process encrypted data (outsourced to the cloud) [5]. 
